1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:06,560
In this video we are going to learn mediator pipeline behavior and fluent validation library.

2
00:00:07,130 --> 00:00:12,920
Mediator is a popular library in dotnet used for implementing the mediator pattern.

3
00:00:13,580 --> 00:00:20,990
One of its powerful feature is pipeline behaviors, which allows us to introduce additional logic into

4
00:00:20,990 --> 00:00:27,650
the request handling process such as validation, logging, exception handling, and performance tracking.

5
00:00:28,610 --> 00:00:32,840
Pipeline behaviors act as a middleware in the mediator library.

6
00:00:32,900 --> 00:00:39,920
They wrap around the request handling process, enabling us to implement cross-cutting concerns without

7
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:42,200
cluttering the handlers themselves.

8
00:00:43,070 --> 00:00:49,850
A pipeline behavior is essentially a class that implements I pipeline behavior interface with t request

9
00:00:49,850 --> 00:00:50,900
and t response.

10
00:00:50,930 --> 00:00:58,700
It provides the handle method where you can execute the code before and after the next delegate is invoked.

11
00:00:59,570 --> 00:01:03,800
Here you can see that how mediator pipeline behaviors works.

12
00:01:03,800 --> 00:01:07,490
You can see that mediator will be trigger the handle method.

13
00:01:07,490 --> 00:01:11,960
But before that we can invoke the preprocessor behavior.

14
00:01:11,960 --> 00:01:16,160
And after that you can invoke the post-processor behavior.

15
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:18,350
So you can see an example of that.

16
00:01:18,350 --> 00:01:22,640
The request comes into the first middleware and perform the first logic.

17
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:28,760
And after that invoke the next method in order to pass the middleware to and middleware two.

18
00:01:28,760 --> 00:01:36,350
Also implement the actual logic and invoke the next middleware with next method, and after that, and

19
00:01:36,350 --> 00:01:42,710
middleware three is the last middleware that performs the actual logic and response back to the middleware

20
00:01:42,710 --> 00:01:43,880
two and one.

21
00:01:43,880 --> 00:01:49,130
That means this will be invoke post-process behaviors and return back to the response.

22
00:01:49,130 --> 00:01:52,970
So here you can see another example which is the tracing behavior.

23
00:01:52,970 --> 00:01:57,500
So in the pipeline behavior this is tracing the logic.

24
00:01:57,500 --> 00:01:59,690
And after that invoking await.

25
00:01:59,690 --> 00:02:00,560
Next method.

26
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:03,710
And this will be handled actual handler method.

27
00:02:03,710 --> 00:02:07,280
And after that this will goes to post pipeline behavior.

28
00:02:07,280 --> 00:02:12,080
And this will be traced after operation under the post processor behavior.

29
00:02:12,080 --> 00:02:15,350
And here you can see basic code example.

30
00:02:15,350 --> 00:02:20,180
That is a pipeline behavior that locks the execution time of the request.

31
00:02:20,180 --> 00:02:22,160
This is the logging behavior.

32
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:27,350
And in the handle method this will be basically logging the execution time.

33
00:02:27,350 --> 00:02:30,800
And after that handle the actual handle logic.

34
00:02:31,370 --> 00:02:34,490
So this was the mediator pipeline behaviors.

35
00:02:34,490 --> 00:02:41,630
And now we will focus on the fluent validation library and how mediator pipelines work with the fluent

36
00:02:41,630 --> 00:02:42,800
validation libraries.

37
00:02:42,830 --> 00:02:44,480
What is fluent validation?

38
00:02:44,510 --> 00:02:49,970
Fluent validation is a dotnet library for building strongly typed validation rules.

39
00:02:49,970 --> 00:02:57,770
It is known for its clean syntax and ease of use, making validation logics more readable and maintainable,

40
00:02:58,580 --> 00:03:05,270
so we can integrate fluent validation and with mediator to validate requests before they reach the actual

41
00:03:05,300 --> 00:03:05,900
handler.

42
00:03:05,900 --> 00:03:11,360
This integration happens within a pipeline behavior, especially the pipeline behaviors.

43
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:19,370
So fluent validation allows you to define validation rules in a separate classes, using a fluent interface

44
00:03:19,370 --> 00:03:24,530
to specify conditions that each property of your models must satisfy.

45
00:03:24,530 --> 00:03:27,260
You can see the image on the slide.

46
00:03:27,260 --> 00:03:33,050
This is an example of validation class for a request model specifying various validation rules.

47
00:03:34,190 --> 00:03:37,280
So combining mediator with fluent validation.

48
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:44,240
Centralized or cross-cutting concerns like validation making our code cleaner and more maintainable.

49
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:48,680
It is also ensures that our business logic only process valid data.

50
00:03:48,770 --> 00:03:50,690
So this will be an example.

51
00:03:50,690 --> 00:03:58,100
This is working Pre-processor that is validating the create product command and checking the members

52
00:03:58,100 --> 00:04:00,530
name, category, image file price.

53
00:04:00,530 --> 00:04:04,310
And these should not be empty and the price should be greater than zero.

